[{"id":"VR914708","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an incident light beam moving to the right through two slits that are distance d apart. Two dashed lines indicate the path of light emerging from the slits and are angle theta from the horizon.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR914708.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The figure shows a close-up view of two closely-spaced slits separated by a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span>. A beam of light of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span> is incident on the slits from the left. The two dashed lines indicate possible paths for light emerging from the slits and meeting at a common point on a distant screen (not shown). The two paths are nearly parallel, and can be considered to be at the same angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span> from the original beam direction. If the two paths meet at a brightness maximum in the interference pattern formed on the screen, which of the following is a possible expression for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span>?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR914708_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the inverse sine of the fraction with numerator 2 lambda, and denominator d, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the inverse sine of the fraction with numerator 2 lambda, and denominator d, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the inverse sine of the fraction with numerator lambda, and denominator 2 d, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the inverse sine of the fraction with numerator lambda, and denominator 2 d, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mi>λ</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the inverse tangent of the fraction with numerator 2 lambda, and denominator d, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the inverse tangent of the fraction with numerator 2 lambda, and denominator d, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the inverse tangent of the fraction with numerator lambda, and denominator 2 d, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the inverse tangent of the fraction with numerator lambda, and denominator 2 d, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mi>λ</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></span></span></p>"],"answer":0}]